As per the [ExpressJS Error Handling Guide](https://expressjs.com/en/guide/error-handling.html), it's really easy to set up custom error handling for the whole app in Express 5;

```js
const bodyParser = require('body-parser')
const methodOverride = require('method-override')

app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({
  extended: true
}))
app.use(bodyParser.json())
app.use(methodOverride())
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  // logic
})
```
*Result: `app` uses custom error handling*

However, I noticed the same syntax doesn't seem to work when trying to apply error handling middleware to a `Router`:

```js
const bodyParser = require('body-parser')
const methodOverride = require('method-override')

router = express.Router();

router.use(methodOverride())
router.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  // logic
})

app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({
  extended: true
}))
app.use(bodyParser.json())
app.use(router)
```
*Result: custom error handling defined on `router` is never called*

